{"source_key":"sha256-57a0ef58ecdd57e62937c2289b37339b","record_index":2057,"record_hash":"sha256:d66c78e4ed020c9a16baa25d34bd926c0312597538925b309ea9c9f216bf97a8","timestamp":"2026-05-26T13:24:23.592Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"assistant","text":"Yeah. The right bar here is: **no stored field without a concrete reader-side job**.\n\nFor this feature, the purpose is narrow: fix false/weak PR association while still recovering the real session trail. So the schema should only store evidence needed to answer:\n\n- Was this branch/PR merely ambient?\n- Did a dirty file from the previous turn become part of a commit?\n- Which applied branch/review/change did that commit belong to?\n- Was that commit/file already there before?\n\nThat justifies commit IDs, branch-to-review/change keys, and committed file fingerprints. It does **not** justify rich nested review/change objects, raw committed paths, or command-specific plumbing spread through mutation code.\n\nI’ll keep using that lens: add the smallest durable fact that supports the query, prefer deriving behavior at read time, cap anything that can grow, keep legacy compatibility, and delete weaker heuristics when stronger evidence replaces them. That’s the difference between a fix and a little schema snowball.","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-26T13:24:23.592Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"assistant","phase":"final_answer"}}}